<DOC><DOCNO> AP880624-0269 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0023EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   06-24 0557</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0582</SECOND><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Rowntree PLC has agreed to a sweetened, $4.5billion buyout offer from Swiss foods giant Nestle SA, ending themonths-long ``candy bar war'' for the British confectioner.   Nestle's 2.55 billion-pound offer accepted Thursday edges outrival bidder Jacobs Suchard AG, a Swiss chocolate and coffeeconcern, to create the world's second-largest confectioner behindU.S.-based Mars Inc.   The bid for Rowntree, maker of the Kit Kat candy bar, is thelargest offer for a British company by a foreign concern.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Federal Communications Commission hasvoted to impose the first fine under its decency standards on aMissouri television station for broadcasting a ``pandering andtitillating'' sex comedy during prime time.   The FCC voted 2-1 Thursday to levy the maximum $2,000 fine onKZKC-TV, a UHF station in Kansas City, for showing the movie``Private Lessons'' at 8 p.m., a time at which the agency saidchildren were likely to be watching.   The movie, broadcast May 26, 1987, included scenes of abare-breasted woman that the FCC said ``were neither isolated norfleeting.''</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Consumer electronics aren't just for yuppies,according to an industry group that released a Gallup survey thatfound nearly two-thirds of American homes owned a videocassetterecorder.   Ownership of VCRs has mushroomed to 65 percent of U.S.households, the Electronic Industries Association, which sponsoredthe nationwide telephone survey of 1,008 adults this spring, saidThursday.   Televisions, which topped the popularity list, were owned by 99percent of the households surveyed.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The communications industry is expected to growat an average annual rate of 10.1 percent over the next five years,down from its 10.9 percent expansion pace for the previous fiveyears, according to an investment banking firm specializing inmedia deals.   The projected growth rate for the period 1988 through 1992,however, should exceed both anticipated 7.5 percent growth of theoverall economy and the estimated expansion in other leadingindustries, the firm Veronis, Suhler andamp; Associates Inc. reportedThursday.   The report covers revenue forecasts for radio, television,newspapers, magazines, recorded music, books, films and informationservices.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The heads of the three major televisionnetworks have asked Congress to ensure that America's system offree local broadcasting be preserved in the race for highdefinition TV now being developed.   The three network chiefs said Thursday that any decisions thatwill move the U.S. television industry to an improved picturequality should protect the 140 million TV sets currently in use.   Broadcasters fear they could be left out if others in the TVindustry, such as cable TV and makers of videocassette players,adopt a high definition TV transmission standard that is notcompatible with existing TV sets.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market dipped Thursday in moderate trading asinvestors cashed in the strong gains of the previous two sessions.The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, up nearly 70 pointsin the two previous sessions, fell 3.91 points to 2,148.29.   The dollar finished higher after gyrating in world trading. Goldprices edged lower.   Bond prices finished little changed after an early rally.   Soybean, corn and wheat futures prices fell, while oats hit newhighs over fears of further drought damage to the crop.</TEXT></DOC>